<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/39612777-jensha-buskey"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1423123687i/39612777._UY100_CR10,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/39612777-jensha-buskey">Jensha Buskey</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Cate, you can just put a note on it to say that the reader can choose which way they want to read it. I&apos;m assuming that most people who are familiar w<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Cate, you can just put a note on it to say that the reader can choose which way they want to read it. I'm assuming that most people who are familiar with Ali Smith's work were aware of the uniqueness of this publication ahead of reading it. I knew, so I chose. In my version, the Francescho part was printed first, but I chose to start in the middle of the book, with the George part. <a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
