  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3953731142" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3953731142" />
    <a title="John Banks" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/107042319-john-banks"><img alt="John Banks" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1592479516p2/107042319.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3953731142?book_show_action=true">Apr 21, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John Banks" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John Banks" href="/user/show/107042319-john-banks">John Banks</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141025209" href="/book/show/25371939-how-to-be-both">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3953731142" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1672045756371054416">4.5<br/><br/>Winner of 2014 Costa Novel of the Year, shortlisted for Booker prize 2014, winner 2015 Women&apos;s Prize for Fiction, Winner of the 2014 Goldsmiths Prize.<br/><br/>Ali Smith&apos;s How to be Both is a clever, playful novel in structure and language. At times it wears the brilliance on its sleeve, while at the same time sardonically laughing at itself. It&apos;s a rich, joyous and yes indulgent display of the powers of art. A searing artistic gaze glares out from the pages, almost daring the reader to stare right bac</span>
  <span id="freeText1672045756371054416" style="display:none">4.5<br /><br />Winner of 2014 Costa Novel of the Year, shortlisted for Booker prize 2014, winner 2015 Women's Prize for Fiction, Winner of the 2014 Goldsmiths Prize.<br /><br />Ali Smith's How to be Both is a clever, playful novel in structure and language. At times it wears the brilliance on its sleeve, while at the same time sardonically laughing at itself. It's a rich, joyous and yes indulgent display of the powers of art. A searing artistic gaze glares out from the pages, almost daring the reader to stare right back and ask so what, then that gaze changes to be kinder and gentler, inviting you in. I get the sense that this is a typical Smith feature, a strange kind of sardonic, distanced, compassion.<br /><br />How to be Both provides a thoughtful, wry and even at times funny treatise about how we look and see: as children, as parents, as lovers, as friends, as mourners, as the deceased, as voyeurs, as artists, as art lovers; as readers, as writers. It's about how all this looking and seeing can deceive us and yet how by giving in to the deception, even laughing with it, we find moments of love and joy. The novel holds up for us a kind of artistic, even literary seeing, that while mired in the everyday material stuff of life can also transcend it. <br /><br />How to be Both focuses on themes of time and memory: how time twists, distorts and even conveys our looking. How looking is historically shaped, including through gender and desire and our changing technologies and devices for looking. Smith celebrates how art and literature can shape shift, defying time and mortality (or can it?) and in the process transform us and our messy lives. In short, it's the kind of brilliant novel that I adore and I know Smith will be among my favorite contemporary novelists.<br /><br />The novel's playful structure, two interlinked stories that can be read in either order, mostly worked for me, even if a little ungainly. For my read, the first half is the story of George (a teenage girl) whose mother has recently died. In the midst of grief and mourning, dealing with the fallout of this loss, including a somewhat absent father self-medicating with the bottle and a rather lost younger brother, George is grasping at her memories in an effort to hold on to her mother. These memories include a shared spontaneous trip to Italy to view art and particularly a 15th century fresco painted by Francesco del Cossa at the Ducal Palazzo Schifanoia in Ferrara. The story of this artist, Francescho, and her eye (narrated as a first person I, stream of consciousness style in sections) made up the second half of my read. <br /><br />The playful interchange between these two visions is at the heart of this book: the camera eye of young 21st century George and the eye (I) of the painter, Francescho. Francescho's eye is surrealistically resurrected as an observer of George's life, including of how this life is mediated through contemporary visual media (photos and digital devices). So just as in the first half we have George (and her mother) as observers and interpreters of 15th century art, in the later sections we have this haunting presence of Francescho, and perhaps of 15th century artistic culture and sensibility, staring right back at and interrogating the 21C world and its visual cultures. This interplay is structurally and stylistically fascinating and through it you sense the wry, compassionately playful, writerly vision of Smith orchestrating and pulling the strings. Yes it's manipulative, yes the structure feels somewhat forced at times, and yes it works wonderfully.<br /><br />Smith even gives us winks and nudges about how we should approach this dualistic, interleaved two story structure: essentially as a fresco in which we peal back the layers, or as a series of digital images that we can reproduce and rearrange, collage fashion. Perhaps try both. <br /><br />"You have the very first version of the fresco underneath the skin, as it were, of the real fresco. There's a fresco on the wall: there it is, you and I look at it, we see it right in front of us; underneath that there's another version of the story and it may or may not be connected to the surface. And they're both in front of our eyes, but you can only see one, or you see one first. So it's about the understory."<br /><br />It's messy and convoluted. As is this review :) Does the structural playfulness get out of hand and away from Smith somewhat. Perhaps. But I love this literary dance (and dancing does feature as an interesting metaphor) as the fresco imagery and pieces fly off in all kinds of different directions for the attentive reader to follow. It's almost as though Smith invites us to join in this literary, painterly dance and trace our own figures through it.<br /><br />"Because if things really did happen simultaneously it'd be like reading a book but one in which all the lines of the text have been overprinted, like each page is actually two pages but with one superimposed on the other to make it unreadable"<br /><br />Smith even ironically pokes fun at reader's like me: "Oh very clever, very clever, they think they're so clever always answering questions with questions."<br /><br />George reflecting while viewing the fresco: "... when you look away from this painting at the others in the room it's like they've all been dwarfed. After this painting they look flat and old-fashioned, as if they're stale dramas and pretending to be real. This one at least admits the whole thing's a performance" <br /><br />Oh how gloriously meta. But is this the kind of vain meta games that at the end leave the reader asking, "Well, OK but what's the point"?<br /><br />And yet the language Smith weaves is deeply personal. In an exchange between George and her friend H (Helena Fisker) involving shared music list:<br /><br />"Even more strange and fine is the fact that someone has wanted her to hear them, and not just someone, but Helena Fisker. It is like having a conversation without needing to say anything. It is also like H is trying to find a language that will make personal sense to George's ears. No one has ever done this before for George. She has spent her whole life speaking other people's languages. It is new to her. The newness of it has a sort of power that can make the old things - as old as those old songs, even as ancient as Latin itself - a kind of new, but a kind that doesn't dismiss their, what would you call it?"<br /><br />This power is evident when describing the artist's craft of seeing as:<br /><br /> "Cause that's all the life of a painter is, the seen and gone disappearing into the air, rain, seasons, years, the ravenous beaks of the ravens. All we are is eyes looking for the unbroken or the edges where the broken bits might fit each other". <br /><br />There are many dazzling passages like this that resonate across the two stories in profoundly moving ways and I will be exploring and reflecting on these threads for awhile yet I think. For example, Smith has fun and games with Latin phrases and roots of words and this also clearly links as well to the earlier classical Latin influences on 15th Century Renaissance Italy and how the traces of this are still carried in contemporary English. Smith revels throughout this book in the complex web of influence in terms of language, iconography, religion etc and the temporality of such influences. I've enjoyed following the various threads of this that she weaves through How to be Both. <br /><br />So why not a 5 from me? It just falls short because the cleverness of it all shows through the layers a little too often, pulling me out of the literary dance, the imagery and the language. I'm still considering whether this is a fault and perhaps I will revise up to a 5. I'm eager to read much more Ali Smith and I will be picking up Autumn as my next read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1672045756371054416" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


